T-cell receptor β hypervariable region clustering in sample 111H.

Maria S. Benítez-Cantos, Carlos Cano, Armando Blanco

15-04-2020

1 Preface and aims

Hypervariable region identification (HVR) comprises two main steps:

  1. V and J segments alignment
  2. Sequencing error correction (or HVR unique sequences collapsing into clonotypes)

We are currently exploring different approaches for the second step, including:

  • Sequencing error correction software: a combination of Pollux and Fiona was chosen based on the results of Song et al. Deprecated. Explored in the notebook pollux_fiona_on_111H_sample.
  • Hierarchical clustering (Levenshtein distance): along with optimal number of clusters metrics and different linkage methods.
  • Ad hoc approach: including the previous approaches or not, but taking into account abundance, reading frame and distance information.

Since sequencing error correction softwares did not yield optimal results, a clustering step for HVR sequences collapsing is required.

2.1 V and J alignment

Old version: The function vj_alignment has been improved. The updated version (with detailed explanation) is on the "HVR_identification_pipeline_test" notebook (V alignment without IMGT gaps, Cys check fixed, changed output fields).

###################################################### (3.1)
############ VJ alignment OLD VERSION !!!!!!!!!!!!!! ##########
###################################################### (3.1)

vj_alignment <- function(reads, Vsegments, Jsegments, numCores = detectCores() - 4, gapOpening = 1){
  #' Align V and J segments in a set of reads to delimit the hypervariable region (HVR)
  #' 
  #' @param reads A \code{DNAStringSet} or a \code{QualityScaledDNAStringSet} containing the reads.
  #' @param Vsegments A \code{DNAStringSet} with the V segments trimmed up to the Cys codon.
  #' @param Jsegments A \code{DNAStringSet} with the J segments trimmed from the Phe codon.
  #' @param numCores Number of cores to execute the function in parallel.
  #' @param gapOpening Penalty for opening a gap in the alignment.
  #' @return A \code{data.frame} with V and J alignment information and HVR sequence, quality and reading frame.
  
  results <- dplyr::bind_rows(mclapply(mc.cores = numCores, X = 1:length(reads), FUN = function(i){
    
  read <- reads[i]  
  
  # Get the read ID
  read_id <- names(read)
  
  #########################################
  ############## V ALIGNMENT ##############
  #########################################
  
  ### Perform 147 V alignments and get the score only ###
  v_alignment1 <- pairwiseAlignment(pattern = Vsegments, 
                                 subject = read,
                                 type = "global-local",
                                 scoreOnly = TRUE,
                                 gapOpening = gapOpening)
  
  ### Select the segment with the best score ###
  best_v <- Vsegments[which.max(v_alignment1)]
  best_v_complete <- v_segments[which.max(v_alignment1)]
  v_match <- names(best_v)
  
  ### Perform a complete pairwise alignment with the best match ###
  v_alignment2 <- pairwiseAlignment(pattern = best_v,
                                 subject = read,
                                 type = "global-local",
                                 scoreOnly = FALSE,
                                 gapOpening = gapOpening)
  
  ### Get V alignment information ###
  v_score <- score(v_alignment2)
  v_identity <- pid(v_alignment2, type = "PID3")
  v_start <- start(Views(v_alignment2))
  v_end <- end(Views(v_alignment2))
  
  
  if (v_score < 0) { # If V score is negative, cys_check nor J alignment are performed 
    
    cys_check <- NA
    cys_status <- NA

    j_match <- NA
    j_score <- NA
    j_identity <- NA
    j_start <- NA
    j_end <- NA
    phe_check <- NA
    
    read_cys_start <- NA
    HVR_seq <- NA
    HVR_qual <- NA
    HVR_frame <- NA

    
  } else { # Only find Cys and align J if V score is positive
  
    #########################################
    ####### FIND CYS, HANDLE INDELS #########
    #########################################
    
    # Cys coordinates in the alignment, ideally
    cys_start <- 310
    cys_end <- 312
    
    # If there is any insertion in the read, Cys coordinates will be shifted in the alignment
    v_ins <- unlist(deletion(v_alignment2)) # IRanges with V insertions
    alg_cys_start <- cys_start + sum(width(v_ins[start(v_ins) <= cys_start])) # Cys start in alignment
    alg_cys_end <- cys_end + sum(width(v_ins[start(v_ins) <= cys_end])) # Cys end in alignment
    
    
    # Find Cys coordinates in the read
    v_del <- unlist(insertion(v_alignment2)) # IRanges with deletions in subject (mostly IMGT gaps)
    
    num_v_del <- length(v_del) # Number of deletions (of any length)
    shift <- c(0, cumsum(width(v_del))[-num_v_del]) 
    v_del_sft <- shift(v_del, shift) # Fix coordinates
    subject_gaps <- sum(width(v_del_sft[end(v_del_sft) < alg_cys_start])) # Number of gaps in subject before Cys in the alignment
    
    read_cys_start <- v_start + alg_cys_start - subject_gaps -1 # Cys start in the read
    
    
    # Get aligned Cys sequences in pattern and subject
    cys_subject <- subseq(alignedSubject(v_alignment2), start = alg_cys_start, end = alg_cys_end) # Cys sequence in subject
    gap_subject <- unlist(gregexpr(pattern = "-", text = cys_subject)) # Gap position in subject (deletion), if any
    
    cys_pattern <- subseq(alignedPattern(v_alignment2), start = alg_cys_start, end = alg_cys_end) # Cys sequence in pattern
    gap_pattern <- unlist(gregexpr(pattern = "-", text = cys_pattern)) # Gap position in pattern (insertion), if any
    
    # Check Cys sequence in subject
    if (cys_subject %in% c("TGT", "TGC")) { # Cys codon found
    
      cys_check <- TRUE
    
      if (cys_subject == cys_pattern) { # Same Cys codon in pattern and subject
        cys_status <- "Match"
    
      } else { # Different Cys codon in pattern and subject
        cys_status <- paste0("Pseudomatch (", cys_pattern," > ", cys_subject, ")")
      }
    
    } else if (all(gap_pattern > 0)) { # Insertion in subject, fix it by removing it
      cys_status <- paste0("Insertion (", cys_pattern," > ", cys_subject, "), removed")
    
      read_ins_pos <- read_cys_start + as.numeric(gap_pattern) -1 # Insertion position in read
      
      # Delete insertion in read
      fix_read <- as.character(read)
      fix_qual <- quality(read)
      stringr::str_sub(fix_read, read_ins_pos[1], read_ins_pos[length(read_ins_pos)]) <- "" # Remove Cys insertion in the read
      stringr::str_sub(fix_qual, read_ins_pos[1], read_ins_pos[length(read_ins_pos)]) <- "" # Remove Cys insertion in the quality string
      fix_qual <- as(fix_qual, new.quality.class) # Convert to PhredQuality class
      read_id <- names(read)
      read <- QualityScaledDNAStringSet(fix_read, fix_qual) # Rebuild QualityScaledDNAStringSet without Cys insertion
      names(read) <- read_id
      
      cys_codon <- subseq(read, start = read_cys_start, end = read_cys_start + 2)
      cys_check <- ifelse(cys_codon %in% c("TGT", "TGC"), TRUE, FALSE)
      
    } else if (all(gap_subject > 0)) { # Deletion in subject
      cys_status <- paste0("Deletion (", cys_pattern," > ", cys_subject, ")")
      cys_check <- FALSE
    
    } else { # Mismatch
      cys_status <- paste0("Mismatch (", cys_pattern," > ", cys_subject, ")")
      cys_check <- FALSE
    }
    
    
    
    
    
    #########################################
    ############## J ALIGNMENT ##############
    #########################################
    
    ### Remove V match from the read
    remaining <- subseq(read, start = read_cys_start + 3) # Align J from Cys codon (not included)
    
    ### Perform 16 J alignments and get the score only
    j_alignment1 <- pairwiseAlignment(pattern = Jsegments, 
                                   subject = remaining,
                                   type = "global-local",
                                   scoreOnly = TRUE,
                                   gapOpening = gapOpening)
    
    ### Select the segment with the best score
    best_j <- Jsegments[which.max(j_alignment1)]
    j_match <- names(best_j)
    
    ### Perform a complete pairwise alignment with the best match
    j_alignment2 <- pairwiseAlignment(pattern = best_j,
                                   subject = remaining,
                                   type = "global-local",
                                   scoreOnly = FALSE,
                                   gapOpening = gapOpening)
    
    ### Get J alignment information
    j_score <- score(j_alignment2)
    j_identity <- pid(j_alignment2, type = "PID3")
    j_start <- start(Views(j_alignment2)) + read_cys_start + 2 # Get the coordinates **in the read**, not in the sequence without the V match
    j_end <- end(Views(j_alignment2)) + read_cys_start + 2
    
    ### Check if the first codon is a Phe
    phe_codon <- subseq(read, start = j_start, end = j_start + 2)
    phe_check <- phe_codon %in% c("TTT", "TTC")
    
    
    
    
    
    #########################################
    ############## HVR LOCATION #############
    #########################################
    
    ### Get HVR sequence and sequencing quality
    HVR <- subseq(read, start = read_cys_start, end = j_start + 2)
    HVR_seq <- as.character(HVR)
    HVR_qual <- as.character(quality(HVR))
    
    # Find out HVR frame (0: Cys and Phe in frame; 1 OR 2: out of frame)
    HVR_frame <- nchar(HVR_seq) %% 3
    
    if (HVR_frame != 0) { # If the remainder is 1, frame = 2 and viceversa
      HVR_frame <- ifelse(HVR_frame == 1, 2, 1)
    }
  }
  
  
    
  
  #########################################
  ################# OUTPUT ################
  #########################################
  
  df <- data.frame(
    read_ID = read_id,
    
    V_match = v_match,
    V_score = v_score,
    V_identity = v_identity,
    V_start = v_start,
    Cys_check = cys_check,
    Cys_status = cys_status,
    
    J_match = j_match,
    J_score = j_score,
    J_identity = j_identity,
    J_start = j_start,
    J_end = j_end,
    Phe_check = phe_check,
    
    HVR_start = read_cys_start,
    HVR_sequence = HVR_seq,
    HVR_quality = HVR_qual,
    HVR_frame = HVR_frame
    
  ) %>% mutate(read_ID = as.character(read_ID),
               V_match = as.character(V_match),
               J_match = as.character(J_match),
               Cys_status = as.character(Cys_status),
               HVR_sequence = as.character(HVR_sequence),
               HVR_quality = as.character(HVR_quality))

  
  return(df)
  }))
}

2.2 Optimal number of clusters

Optimal number of clusters are devised from the result of a hierarchical clustering with complete linkage of all VJ families separately.

The as.clustrange function in the WeightedCluster package estimates the best number of clusters according to several measures and the value of these statistics:

  • PBC - Point Biserial Correlation: Measure of the capacity of the clustering to reproduce the distances.
  • HG - Hubert’s Gamma: Measure of the capacity of the clustering to reproduce the distances (order of magnitude).
  • HGSD - Hubert’s Somers’ D: Measure of the capacity of the clustering to reproduce the distances (order of magnitude) taking into account ties in distances.
  • ASW - Average Silhouette Width: Coherence of assignments. High coherence indicates high between-group distances and strong within-group homogeneity.
  • ASWw - Average Silhouette Width (weighted): As previous, for floating point weights.
  • CH - Calinski-Harabasz index: Pseudo F computed from the distances.
  • CHsq - Calinski-Harabasz index: As previous, but using squared distances.
  • R2 - Pseudo R2: Share of the discrepancy explained by the clustering solution (only to compare partitions with identical number of groups).
  • R2sq - Pseudo R2: As previous, but using squared distances.
  • HC - Hubert’s C: Gap between the partition obtained and the best partition theoretically possible with this number of groups and these distances.

This function can not be applied to VJ families with 2 or less unique HVR sequences, therefore, of the 89 VJ families where clustering is performed (more than one HVR), only 68 are shown in the following table:

###################################################### (12.1)
############# Optimal number of clusters #############
###################################################### (12.1)

opt_num_clust <- function(data_ec, linkage, weighted = FALSE){
  
  #########################################
  ############# Prepare data ##############
  #########################################
  
  ### Unique reads
  data_ec_uniq <- plyr::ddply(data_ec,.(V_match, J_match, HVR_sequence, HVR_frame), nrow)
  data_ec_uniq <- data_ec_uniq %>% dplyr::rename(Counts = V1)
  
  vj_fam <- split(data_ec_uniq, paste0(data_ec_uniq$V_match, " / ", data_ec_uniq$J_match)) # Split data frame by VJ match into list of data frames

  ### Remove VJ families with < 2 members
  single_idx <- unlist(lapply(vj_fam, function(x){nrow(x) <= 2})) # Logic vector for one- and two-membered families
  vj_sgl_member <- bind_rows(vj_fam[single_idx]) # Data frame with one member clonotypes
  
  ### List of data frames with VJ families with more than two clonotypes
  vj_groups <- vj_fam[!single_idx] 
  vj_groups <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){
    df <- x
    rownames(df) <- 1:nrow(df)
    return(df)
  })
  
  ### Create DNAStringSet
  vj_groups_dss <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){ # List of QualityScaledDNAStringSet with VJ families with more than one clonotype
  dss <- DNAStringSet(x[,"HVR_sequence"]) # Sequences
  # qual <- as(x[,"HVR_quality"], new.quality.class) # Quality strings (PhredQuality class)
  # qsdss <- QualityScaledDNAStringSet(dss, qual) # Get QualityScaledDNAStringSet
  ids <- rownames(x)
  # names(qsdss) <- ids
  # return(qsdss)
  names(dss) <- ids
  return(dss)
  })
  
  # return(vj_groups)

  ########################################
  ###### Optimal number of clusters ######
  ########################################
  
  family_names <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){

    v_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"V_match"])
    j_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"J_match"])
    family_name <- paste(v_name, j_name, "N =", nrow(vj_groups[[idx]]))
    return(family_name)
  })
  
  cluster_metrics <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){

    ### LEVENSHTEIN DISTANCE ###
  
    df <- vj_groups_dss[idx][[1]]
    ld <- stringDist(df, method = "levenshtein", upper = TRUE, diag = TRUE)
    # ld_mat <- as.matrix(ld)
    # diag(ld_mat) <- NA
  
    ### HIERARCHICAL CLUSTERING ###
    if (weighted) {
      ld_hc <- hclust(ld, method = linkage, members =  vj_groups[[idx]][,"Counts"])
    } else {
      ld_hc <- hclust(ld, method = linkage)
    }
    
    ### SILHOUETTE COEFICIENT ###
    hcRange <- as.clustrange(ld_hc, diss=ld, ncluster = ifelse(nrow(vj_groups[[idx]]) > 10, 10, nrow(vj_groups[[idx]])))
    # print(summary(hcRange))
    # sil_plt <- plot(hcRange, stat = c("ASWw", "HG", "PBC", "HGSD"), lwd = 2)
    
    return(summary(hcRange))
  })
  
  names(cluster_metrics) <- family_names
  
  cluster_metrics2 <- lapply(cluster_metrics, function(df){
  df2 <- data.frame(t(df[,1]))
  colnames(df2) <- rownames(df)
  return(df2)
  })

  cluster_metrics2 <- bind_rows(cluster_metrics2, .id="VJ_family")
  
  return(cluster_metrics2)
}

2.3 Hierarchical clustering

Linkage methods

The hclust function can perform a hierarchical clustering with the following linkage methods:

  • average: Average of distances.
  • single: Merging of the groups with closest observations.
  • complete: Minimization of diameter of each new group (very sensitive to atypical data).
  • centroid: Minimization of distances between medoids.
  • mcquitty: Depends on previous mergings.
  • median: Depends on previous mergings.
  • ward.D: Minimization of residual variance.
  • ward.D2: Minimization of residual variance.

All methods have been tested in all 89 VJ families (dendrograms located in /plots/dendrograms_sample_111H/linkage_methods, along with an .ods file with some annotations) and some interesting cases were manually studied. single, complete, ward.D and ward.D2 methods are the most promising.

Weights

The members argument of the hclust function allows us to specify the frequency of each unique HVR sequence to use that information in the clustering. A weighted hierarchical clustering was performed for the 4 linkage methods selected.

2.4 Affinity Propagation Clustering

Affinity propagation (AP) is an algorithm that identifies exemplars among data points and forms clusters of data points around these exemplars. It operates by simultaneously considering all data point as potential exemplars and exchanging messages between data points until a good set of exemplars and clusters emerges.

The apcluster function needs a similarity matrix s, hence Levenshtein distance matrices d have been transformed in the same way as the negDistMat function (from the apcluster package) does (s = -d^2):

negDistMat creates a square matrix of mutual pairwise similarities of data vectors as negative distances. The argument r (default is 1) is used to transform the resulting distances by computing the r-th power (use r=2 to obtain negative squared distances as in Frey's and Dueck's demos), i.e., given a distance d, the resulting similarity is computed as s=-d^r.

Pros:

  • Determines the optimal number of clusters by itself.
  • Selects the "exemplars" or representative sample of each cluster (nice!).
  • Identificates k = 1 cases (nice!).

Cons:

  • Lack of an efficient way of specifying the weights (frequency of each HVR) other than using all the reads as input, with an increase in computation time for both distance calculation and clustering.
  • Input preference (p parameter) for each data point to be selected as exemplar highly influences the number of clusters. By default it is set, for all data points, to the median of the similarity matrix values distribution, but this generally overestimates the number of clusters.
  • Finding the optimal value for p is a challenge here.
  • Another option could be to specify p for each HVR taking their weights in account.
  • More info about p and q parameters in the user guide.
ap_clust <- function(data_ec, q = 0.5){

  ### Unique reads
  data_ec_uniq <- plyr::ddply(data_ec,.(V_match, J_match, HVR_sequence, HVR_frame), nrow)
  data_ec_uniq <- data_ec_uniq %>% dplyr::rename(Counts = V1)
  
  vj_fam <- split(data_ec_uniq, paste0(data_ec_uniq$V_match, " / ", data_ec_uniq$J_match)) # Split data frame by VJ match into list of data frames
  
  # ### Duplicated reads
  # vj_fam <- split(data_ec, paste0(data_ec$V_match, " / ", data_ec$J_match)) # Split data frame by VJ match into list of data frames
  
  
  ### Remove single-member VJ families
  single_idx <- unlist(lapply(vj_fam, function(x){nrow(x) == 1})) # Logic vector for one-membered families
  vj_sgl_member <- bind_rows(vj_fam[single_idx]) # Data frame with one member clonotypes
  
  ### List of data frames with VJ families with more than one clonotype
  vj_groups <- vj_fam[!single_idx] 
  vj_groups <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){
    df <- x
    rownames(df) <- 1:nrow(df)
    return(df)
  })
  
  ### Create DNAStringSet
  vj_groups_dss <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){ # List of QualityScaledDNAStringSet with VJ families with more than one clonotype
  dss <- DNAStringSet(x[,"HVR_sequence"]) # Sequences
  # qual <- as(x[,"HVR_quality"], new.quality.class) # Quality strings (PhredQuality class)
  # qsdss <- QualityScaledDNAStringSet(dss, qual) # Get QualityScaledDNAStringSet
  ids <- rownames(x)
  # names(qsdss) <- ids
  # return(qsdss)
  names(dss) <- ids
  return(dss)
  })
  
  
  family_names <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){
    
    v_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"V_match"])
    j_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"J_match"])
    family_name <- paste(v_name, j_name, "N =", nrow(vj_groups[[idx]]))
    return(family_name)
    
  })
    
  
  ap_exemplars <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){
   
    ### NEGATIVE LEVENSHTEIN DISTANCE ###
    df <- vj_groups_dss[idx][[1]]
    ld <- stringDist(df, method = "levenshtein", upper = TRUE, diag = TRUE)
    neg_ld <- -ld^2 # Distance to similarity
    sim_mat <- as.matrix(neg_ld)
    
    ### AFFINITY PROPAGATION CLUSTERING ###
    ld_ap <- apcluster(s = sim_mat, q = q)
    
    
    vj_groups[[idx]]$Freq_rank <- rank(-vj_groups[[idx]][,"Counts"], ties.method = "first")
    exem_df <- vj_groups[[idx]][ld_ap@exemplars, c("Counts", "Freq_rank", "HVR_frame")]
    exem_df$HVR_ID <- ld_ap@exemplars
    # exem_df$VJ_family <- family_name
    
    return(exem_df)
    
    # return(names(ld_ap@exemplars))
  #   
  #   tryCatch(
  #     {
  #       plot(ld_ap)
  #     },
  #     error=function(cond) {
  #       return(NA)
  #     }
  #   )
  })
  
  names(ap_exemplars) <- family_names
  
  df <- bind_rows(ap_exemplars, .id = "VJ_family")
  col_order <- c("VJ_family", "HVR_ID", "Freq_rank", "Counts", "HVR_frame")
  df <- df[, col_order]
  # return(df)
  df <- df[order(df$VJ_family, df$Freq_rank), ]
  
  DT::datatable(df,
              class = 'nowrap compact order-column',
              extensions = c('Buttons',  'FixedColumns', 'RowGroup'),
              options = list(pageLength = 10,
                             lengthMenu = c(10, 20, 50, 100),
                             columnDefs = list(list(className = 'dt-center', targets = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5))),
                             dom = 'Blfrtip',
                             buttons = c('csv', 'excel', 'colvis'),
                             scrollX = TRUE,
                             fixedColumns = TRUE,
                             paging = TRUE,
                             rowGroup = list(dataSrc = 1))) %>%
  
  formatStyle(
    'Freq_rank',
    color = styleInterval(5, c('dodgerblue', 'black')),
    fontWeight = styleInterval(5, c('bold', 'normal'))
  ) %>%
  
  formatStyle(
    'HVR_frame',
    backgroundColor = styleInterval(
      c(0, 1), c("mediumseagreen", "orange", "red")
    )
  )

}

Some situations observed:

  • In general, the picked exemplars are the most frequent HVRs. Those selected with q = 0 are usually correct. q = 0.5 could add some valid exemplars, but also adds out-of-frame exemplars.
  • q = 0 picks the correct exemplar that is missing when q = 0.5, or viceversa.
  • e.g.: TRBV10-3*01 TRBJ1-2*01, TRBV10-3*02 TRBJ2-2*01
  • Special case: TRBV27*01 TRBJ2-2*01 N = 745: for the biggest VJ family in this sample, q = 0 correctly identifies the 3 exemplars (IDs 276, 490, 643) along with two out-of-frame HVRs. However, even though q = 0.5 selects more exemplars, the most abundant (276) is missing.
  • Missing result for q = 0 or q = 0.5.
  • e.g.: TRBV11-1*01 TRBJ2-7*01 (0.5 missing), TRBV12-5*01 TRBJ2-3*01 (0 missing, 0.5 picks an out-of-frame HVR), TRBV20-1*02 TRBJ1-1*01 (0 missing, 0.5 picks the less frequent HVR due to a mismatch with the most frequent)
  • Underestimation of k when N = k.
  • e.g.: TRBV12-3*01 TRBJ2-3*01, TRBV11-1*01 TRBJ2-7*01, TRBV12-5*01 TRBJ2-3*01
  • Both q = 0 and q = 0.5 do not pick the most abundant HVR as the exemplar.
  • TRBV19*01 TRBJ1-1*01, TRBV20-1*01 TRBJ1-1*01, TRBV20-1*02 TRBJ1-1*01 (in all this families N = 2 and k = 1).
  • Even q = 0.5 underestimates the number of exemplars.
  • e.g.: TRBV7-8*01 TRBJ1-1*01

Weighted APC

In order to improve the results provided by the APC we aim to incorporate the frequency of each HVR sequence (i.e. the number of reads with the same V/J match and exact HVR sequence) into the clustering. Two approaches were suggested:

  • Specify p for each HVR: based on abundance (n) modified to be in the same range as the similarity matrix s. Proposed formula:

\[ p_{i} = min(s) + \left(\frac{(max(s) - min(s)) · (n_{i} - min(n))}{max(n) -min(n)}\right) \]

  • Modify s: according to Zhang et al paper (section 1.2.1).

\[ s'_{(i,j)}=\begin{cases} -n_{i}\: d_{(i,j)}^{2} & \text{ if } i\neq j \\ s^{*} & \text{ otherwise } \end{cases} \]

where \(d\) is the distance between sequences and \(s^{*}\) is a small constant called preference (in our case the principal diagonal is 0).

Adjust p for each HVR

Since it is not seem to be an optimal global value for p, we could try to adjust it for each HVR sequence. The main factor that shapes the distribution of p could be the frequency of each sequence, in a way that most frequent HVRs are most likely to be selected as exemplars.

apc_custom_p <- function(data_ec){

  vj_groups <- vj_fam[!single_idx] 
  vj_groups <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){
    df <- x

    vj_groups[[idx]]$Freq_rank <- rank(-vj_groups[[idx]][,"Counts"], ties.method = "first")
    exem_df <- vj_groups[[idx]][ld_ap@exemplars, c("Counts", "Freq_rank", "HVR_frame")]

Modified similarity matrix s

Similarity matrix is multiplied by the frequency of each HVR (column 1 by the frequency of HVR #1 and so on). q = 0 was specified in this case.

apc_custom_s <- function(data_ec, q = 0.5){

  ### Unique reads
  data_ec_uniq <- plyr::ddply(data_ec,.(V_match, J_match, HVR_sequence, HVR_frame), nrow)
  data_ec_uniq <- data_ec_uniq %>% dplyr::rename(Counts = V1)
  
  vj_fam <- split(data_ec_uniq, paste0(data_ec_uniq$V_match, " / ", data_ec_uniq$J_match)) # Split data frame by VJ match into list of data frames
  
  # ### Duplicated reads

Weighted q based on functional diversity

A diversity order, \(q [0, 3]\), should be specified. \(q = 2\) was chosen arbitrarily.

#=============================================================================================
# R code for computing functional diversity in the paper
# Chiu, C.-H. and Chao, A. (2014). Distance-based functional diversity measures
# and their decomposition: a framework based on Hill numbers.PLoS ONE
# 9(7):e100014.
# This code includes two parts:
# (1) Empirical functional diversity
# (2) Empirical functional dissimilarity
#
# Note: The package "Rcpp" must be installed and loaded before running the scripts
#=============================================================================================
library(Rcpp)

#===============================================
#
# (1). Empirical functional diversity
#
#===============================================
#' FD_MLE(q, data, Dij) computes FD of order q based on abundance data.
#' @param q a numeric or a vector of diversity order. The suggested range for q is [0, 3].
#' @param data a vector of species sample frequencies.
#' @param Dij a matrix of distance matrix.
#' @return a numerical vector of FD of orderq .
FD_MLE = function(q, data ,Dij){
  Xi <- data[data!=0]
  distance <- Dij[data!=0, data!=0]
  a <- Xi/sum(Xi)

  Q = sum(distance*(a %*% t(a)))

  Emp <- function(q){
    if(q==1){
      Empirical = exp(-sum(empirical_q1(a, as.matrix(distance), Q)))
    }else{
      Empirical = sum(empirical(a, as.matrix(distance), q, Q))^(1/(1-q))
    }
    Empirical
  }
  sapply(q, Emp)
}

# 
# #===============================================
# #
# # (2). Empirical functional dissimilarity
# #
# #===============================================
# #' FD_Beta(q, data, dij, CU, method) is a function which computes functional dissimilarity measure of order q.
# #' @param q a numeric or a vector of diversity order; The suggested range for q is [0, 3].
# #' @param data a S*N matrix of species sample frequencies with S species (rows), N communities (columns).
# #' @param dij a matrix of distance matrix.
# #' @param CU a character to choose method, "C" for 1-CqN ; "U" for 1-UqN.
# #' @param method a character to choose method, "relative" or "absolute".
# #' @return a numerical vector of functional dissimilarity of order q.
# FD_Beta = function(q, data, dij, CU, method){
#   if(method == "relative") data <- sapply(1:ncol(data), FUN = function(i) data[,i]/sum(data[,i]))
#   N = ncol(data)
#   S = nrow(dij)
#   m = dij
# 
#   M=matrix(rep(t(m), N), ncol = ncol(m), byrow = TRUE)
#   M=matrix(rep(M, N), nrow = nrow(M), byrow = F)
# 
#   alpha = (1/(N)^2)*FD_MLE(q, unlist(data), M)
#   gamma = FD_MLE(q, rowSums(data), dij)
#   beta = gamma/alpha
#   beta[beta<1] = 1
# 
#   MAX.dis = matrix(1, N*S, N*S)
#   for(i in 1:N){
#     MAX.dis[(1:S)+((i-1)*S), (1:S)+((i-1)*S)] = dij
#   }
# 
#   MAX.gamma =  FD_MLE(q, unlist(data), MAX.dis)
#   MAX.beta = MAX.gamma/alpha
#   #MAX.alpha =  FD_MLE(q, unlist(data), MAX.dis)

#   if(CU=="C"){
#     out = (1-beta^(1-q))/(1-MAX.beta^(1-q))
#   }else{
#     out = (1-(beta)^(q-1))/(1-MAX.beta^(q-1))
#   }
#   out[q==1] = log(beta[q==1])/log(MAX.beta[q==1])
#   out
# }

#=========================================================================
#The following two cpp functions are used in the main function FD_MLE.
#=========================================================================
cppFunction(
  "NumericMatrix empirical(NumericVector ai,NumericMatrix dij,float q,float Q){
  const int S = ai.size();
  NumericMatrix temp(S,S);
  for(int i=0;i<S;i++){
  for(int j = 0;j<S;j++){
  temp(i,j) = dij(i,j)*pow((ai[i]*ai[j]/Q),q);
  }
  }
  return(temp);
  }")
cppFunction(
  "NumericMatrix empirical_q1(NumericVector ai,NumericMatrix dij,float Q){
  const int S = ai.size();
  NumericMatrix temp(S,S);
  for(int i=0;i<S;i++){
  for(int j = 0;j<S;j++){
  temp(i,j) = dij(i,j)*(ai[i]*ai[j]/Q)*log(ai[i]*ai[j]/Q);
  }
  }
  return(temp);
  }")
### Functional diversity per VJ family
functdiv_per_fam <- function(data_ec, div_order = 0){
    ### Unique reads
    data_ec_uniq <- plyr::ddply(data_ec,.(V_match, J_match, HVR_sequence,
                                          HVR_frame), nrow)
    data_ec_uniq <- data_ec_uniq %>% dplyr::rename(Counts = V1)
    
    v_name <- gsub("_.*", "", data_ec_uniq$V_match)
    j_name <- gsub("_.*", "", data_ec_uniq$J_match)
    
    data_ec_uniq$VJ_family <- paste0(v_name, "_", j_name)
    
    div <- bind_rows(lapply(unique(data_ec_uniq$VJ_family), function(x){
      
      frequencies <- data_ec_uniq[data_ec_uniq$VJ_family == x, "Counts"] # Frequencies of each HVR
      
      seqs <- data_ec_uniq[data_ec_uniq$VJ_family == x, "HVR_sequence"] # HVR sequences
      
      ld <- as.matrix(stringDist(seqs, method = "levenshtein", upper = TRUE, diag = TRUE)) # Levenshtein distance

      functdiv <- FD_MLE(q = div_order,
                         data = frequencies,
                         Dij = ld)

      df <- data.frame(VJ_family = x,
                       N = length(frequencies),
                       functional_diversity = functdiv)
      
      return(df)
    }))
    
    div[is.na(div)] <- 0 # VJ families with one member often have NA functional diversity, replace with 0
    
    return(div)
  
}

apc_custom_q <- function(data_ec, modifier){

  ### Unique reads
  data_ec_uniq <- plyr::ddply(data_ec,.(V_match, J_match, HVR_sequence, HVR_frame), nrow)
  data_ec_uniq <- data_ec_uniq %>% dplyr::rename(Counts = V1)
  
  vj_fam <- split(data_ec_uniq, paste0(data_ec_uniq$V_match, " / ", data_ec_uniq$J_match)) # Split data frame by VJ match into list of data frames
  
  ### Remove single-member VJ families
  single_idx <- unlist(lapply(vj_fam, function(x){nrow(x) == 1})) # Logic vector for one-membered families
  vj_sgl_member <- bind_rows(vj_fam[single_idx]) # Data frame with one member clonotypes
  
  ### List of data frames with VJ families with more than one clonotype
  vj_groups <- vj_fam[!single_idx] 
  vj_groups <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){
    df <- x
    rownames(df) <- 1:nrow(df)
    return(df)
  })
  
  ### Create DNAStringSet
  vj_groups_dss <- lapply(vj_groups, function(x){ # List of QualityScaledDNAStringSet with VJ families with more than one clonotype
  dss <- DNAStringSet(x[,"HVR_sequence"]) # Sequences
  # qual <- as(x[,"HVR_quality"], new.quality.class) # Quality strings (PhredQuality class)
  # qsdss <- QualityScaledDNAStringSet(dss, qual) # Get QualityScaledDNAStringSet
  ids <- rownames(x)
  # names(qsdss) <- ids
  # return(qsdss)
  names(dss) <- ids
  return(dss)
  })
  
  
  family_names <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){
    
    v_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"V_match"])
    j_name <- gsub("_.*", "", vj_groups[[idx]][1,"J_match"])
    family_name <- paste(v_name, j_name, "N =", nrow(vj_groups[[idx]]))
    return(family_name)
    
  })
    
  
  ap_exemplars <- lapply(1:length(vj_groups), function(idx){
   
    ### NEGATIVE LEVENSHTEIN DISTANCE ###
    df <- vj_groups_dss[idx][[1]]
    ld <- stringDist(df, method = "levenshtein", upper = TRUE, diag = TRUE)
    neg_ld <- -ld^2 # Distance to similarity
    sim_mat <- as.matrix(neg_ld)
    
    ### CALCULATE q FOR EACH VJ FAMILY   ##########################################################
    
    vj_fam <- gsub(" ", "_", gsub(" N.*", "", family_names[[idx]])) # VJ family name (without N=)
    
    modifier <- modifier[modifier$N != 1, ] # Take functional diversity of multi-membered VJ families only
    modifier$functional_diversity <- log10(modifier$functional_diversity) # Applay log10 to functional diversity values
    
    min_s <- 0
    max_s <- 1
    n <- modifier[modifier$VJ_family == vj_fam, "functional_diversity"]
    min_n <- min(modifier$functional_diversity)
    max_n <- max(modifier$functional_diversity)
    
    q <- min_s + ((max_s - min_s) * (n - min_n) / (max_n - min_n))
    
    
    
    ### AFFINITY PROPAGATION CLUSTERING ###
    ld_ap <- apcluster(s = sim_mat, q = q)
    
    
    vj_groups[[idx]]$Freq_rank <- rank(-vj_groups[[idx]][,"Counts"], ties.method = "first")
    exem_df <- vj_groups[[idx]][ld_ap@exemplars, c("Counts", "Freq_rank", "HVR_frame")]
    exem_df$HVR_ID <- ld_ap@exemplars
    # exem_df$VJ_family <- family_name
    
    return(exem_df)
    
    # return(names(ld_ap@exemplars))
  #   
  #   tryCatch(
  #     {
  #       plot(ld_ap)
  #     },
  #     error=function(cond) {
  #       return(NA)
  #     }
  #   )
  })
  
  names(ap_exemplars) <- family_names
  
  df <- bind_rows(ap_exemplars, .id = "VJ_family")
  col_order <- c("VJ_family", "HVR_ID", "Freq_rank", "Counts", "HVR_frame")
  df <- df[, col_order]
  # return(df)
  df <- df[order(df$VJ_family, df$Freq_rank), ]
  
  DT::datatable(df,
              class = 'nowrap compact order-column',
              extensions = c('Buttons',  'FixedColumns', 'RowGroup'),
              options = list(pageLength = 10,
                             lengthMenu = c(10, 20, 50, 100),
                             columnDefs = list(list(className = 'dt-center', targets = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5))),
                             dom = 'Blfrtip',

                             scrollX = TRUE,

Model comparison

For clustering models evaluation and comparison, "true" exemplars were manually selected for all VJ families in sample 111H. Selected exemplars on dendrograms can be seen here. The following table contains a summary of the manual exemplar selection (with comments in special cases):

manual_exemplars <- read.csv("data/manual_exemplars_111H.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

With this "ground truth", we can evaluate the clustering models in terms of supervised classification metrics such as:

  • Accuracy: ratio of correctly predicted observation to the total observations. \[accuracy = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN}\]

  • Recall (sensitivity or true positive rate): ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the all observations in actual class. \[recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN}\]

  • Precision: ratio of correctly predicted positive observations to the total predicted positive observations. \[precision = \frac{TP}{TP+FP}\]

  • F1 score: weighted average of precision and recall (this score takes both false positives and false negatives into account).

\[F_{1} = 2 * \frac{recall · precision}{recall + precision}\]

evaluate_clustering <- function(results, correct_exemplars){
  
  results <- results$x$data # Extract data frame from datatables object
  
  table <- lapply(1:nrow(correct_exemplars), function(x){ # For each VJ family in manual annotation table
    
    true_exemplars <- as.numeric(strsplit(correct_exemplars[x, "Exemplars"], " ")[[1]]) # True exemplars IDs
    
    vj_fam <- results[startsWith(results$VJ_family, str_replace(correct_exemplars[x, "VJ_family"], pattern = "_", replacement = " ")), "VJ_family"][1] # VJ_family has different format in results (TRBV1*01 TRBJ1-1*01 N = 12) vs manual annotation (TRBV1*01_TRBJ1-1*01). This is just a conversion from manual format to results format.
    
    total_HVR <- as.numeric(sub(".*= ", "", vj_fam))

    predicted_exemplars <- results[results$VJ_family == vj_fam, "HVR_ID"]
    
    # TRUE POSITIVES: in both vectors
    tp <- sum(true_exemplars %in% predicted_exemplars)
    # FALSE POSITIVES: in predicted, not in true
    fp <- sum(!(predicted_exemplars %in% true_exemplars))
    # FALSE NEGATIVES: in true, not in predicted
    fn <- sum(!(true_exemplars %in% predicted_exemplars))
    # TRUE NEGATIVES: all the HVR not present in both vectors
    tn <- total_HVR - tp - fp - fn
    
    rw <- data.frame(VJ_family = vj_fam,
                     TP = tp,
                     FP = fp,
                     FN = fn,
                     TN = tn)
    
    return(rw)
  })
  df <- bind_rows(table)
  
  df <- df[!is.na(df$VJ_family), ] # When APC did not converge, VJ family is NA here and should be removed.
  
  df[is.na(df)] <- 0 # Replace NA with 0 in the metrics
 
  TP <- sum(df$TP)
  TN <- sum(df$TN)
  FP <- sum(df$FP)
  FN <- sum(df$FN)
  
  accuracy <- (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
  recall <- TP / (TP + FN)
  precision <- TP / (TP + FP)
  F1 <- 2 * ((recall * precision) / (recall + precision))
  
  # message(paste("Accuracy:", accuracy, "\nRecall:", recall, "\nPrecision:", precision))
  # return(df)
  
  metrics <- data.frame(Accuracy = accuracy,
                        Recall = recall,
                        Precision = precision,
                        F1 = F1)
  
  return(metrics)

  }

This limitation and the fact that this function only adds one new metric for the determination of the optimal number of clusters (delta area), makes us to discard this approach.
